         <h1>Michel Petrucciani, Romantic Of Jazz Piano, Is Dead at 36 </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>Michel Petrucciani , a French jazz pianist and composer with an international following whose keyboard virtuosity earned him comparisons to Art Tatum and Bill Evans , died yesterday at Beth Israel Hospital in Manhattan . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 36 and lived in Manhattan . <br><blue>3</blue>The cause was a pulmonary infection , said a representative of his French record company , Francis Dreyfus Music . <br><blue>4</blue>Mr. Petrucciani was a national hero in France , and his records were best sellers in Europe . <br><blue>5</blue>The French President , Jacques Chirac , was among the many who paid tribute to him yesterday , praising his ability to '' renew jazz , giving himself up to his art with passion , courage and musical genius . '' <br><blue>6</blue>He called him an '' example for everyone . '' <br><blue>7</blue>The career of Mr. Petrucciani , who was considered one of the great romantics of the jazz piano , flourished in spite of a severe physical disability . <br><blue>8</blue>The pianist was born with osteogenesis imperfecta , also known as '' glass bones , '' a disease that stunted his growth ( he was only three feet tall and weighed barely 50 pounds ) and weakened his bones . <br><blue>9</blue>Mr. Petrucciani had to be carried onto the stage , and he used a special attachment to work the sustaining pedal of the piano . <br><blue>10</blue>The ailment did n't affect his hands , however , and he played with a seemingly inexhaustible vigor and enthusiasm . <br><blue>11</blue>Mr. Petrucciani was born to Italian parents in Montpellier , France . <br><blue>12</blue>His family was musical , and as a child he played the drums in a band with his father , Tony , a guitarist , and his brother Louis , a bassist . <br><blue>13</blue>After studying classical music for eight years , he turned to jazz full time because he loved to improvise and wanted to write his own music . <br><blue>14</blue>He began his professional career when he was 15 , playing for the drummer and vibraphonist Kenny Clarke . <br><blue>15</blue>Moving to Paris , he recorded his first album at 17 , and he was appearing regularly at European jazz festivals while still a teen-ager . <br><blue>16</blue>After a visit to New York he toured France in a duo with the saxophonist Lee Konitz , with whom he recorded an album of duets . <br><blue>17</blue>While in California in 1981 , Mr. Petrucciani was discovered by the saxophonist Charles Lloyd , who made him a member of his quartet . <br><blue>18</blue>They toured Europe and recorded an album , '' Montreux ' 82 . '' <br><blue>19</blue>One of his most acclaimed early recordings , '' 100 Hearts '' ( Concord ) , was an album of solos . <br><blue>20</blue>Between 1986 and 1994 , he made seven albums for Blue Note Records , including '' Power of Three '' ( with Wayne Shorter and Jim Hall ) , and an acclaimed album of original songs , '' Michel Plays Petrucciani '' ( Blue Note ) . <br><hr><br><blue>1(1)</blue>: <m_str>comparisons to Art Tatum and Bill Evans</m_str> (1_19) 	<br><blue>2(3)</blue>: <m_str>Montpellier , France</m_str> (11_9) 	<m_str>France</m_str> (16_9) 	<m_str>France</m_str> (4_8) 	<br><blue>3(2)</blue>: <m_str>the piano</m_str> (9_23) 	<m_str>the jazz piano</m_str> (7_16) 	<br><blue>4(2)</blue>: <m_str>classical music</m_str> (13_3) 	<m_str>his own music</m_str> (13_24) 	<br><blue>5(42)</blue>: <m_str>he</m_str> (15_5) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (15_7) 	<m_str>The pianist</m_str> (8_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (15_14) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (16_7) 	<m_str>Mr. Petrucciani</m_str> (9_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (8_21) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (8_24) 	<m_str>him</m_str> (1_18) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (2_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (9_12) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (16_21) 	<m_str>Mr. Petrucciani</m_str> (17_7) 	<m_str>Bill Evans</m_str> (1_24) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (8_38) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (10_6) 	<m_str>him</m_str> (17_19) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (10_12) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (17_23) 	<m_str>Mr. Petrucciani</m_str> (11_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (3_12) 	